<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-102-351 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 048 798</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  July 22 1991 v8 n27 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>TTI helps VAXcluster users tap into locally attached tape drives.andO;(Transitional Technology Inc. introduces React software packagefor letting VAXcluster users share locally attached tape drives)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bowen, Ted Smalley.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Transitional Technology Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   React (Computer program) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionTape Drives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ANAHEIM, Calif.andP;  -- Transitional Technology Inc. (TTI) has introduced aVMS-compatible software package that allows users on VAXclusters to sharelocally attached tape devices.andP;  Previously, users of VAXclusters running VMScould share locally attached tape devices only through an HSC storage server.andM;React software is a TMSCP server package that lets users access local tapesacross CI-based clusters or Local Area VAXclusters (LAVCs).andM;The tape drive is accessed via standard VMS commands, as though it werelinked directly to each node, TTI officials said.andM;Reach also allows tapes to be shared among the nodes of a mixed-interconnectcluster or LAVC, the officials said.andM;With React, users can link tapes directly to system buses such as the VAXBIfor higher performance, while sharing the drive throughout the cluster,according to the officials.andM;React is compatible with VMS 5.4 and subsequent releases.andM;React is available now and is priced at $5,000.andM;Transitional Technology Inc. is located at 5401 E. La Palma Ave., Anaheim, CA92807, (714) 693-1133.andO;</TEXT></DOC>